  4. Cuckoo bird egg lengths, randomization test. Cuckoo birds lay their eggs in other birds nests, making them known as brood parasites. One question relates to whether the size of the cuckoo egg differs depending on the species of the host bird.2 [@Latter:1902]

    library(tidyverse)
library(Stat2Data)
library(infer)
library(openintro)

data(Cuckoo)

F_obs <- Cuckoo %>%
  specify(Length ~ Bird) %>%
  calculate(stat = "F") %>% pull()

set.seed(4747)
Cuckoo %>%
  specify(Length ~ Bird) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "F") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = stat)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = IMSCOL["green", "full"]) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = F_obs, color = IMSCOL["red", "full"], size = 1) +
  labs(
    x = "F statistic for randomized egg lengths", 
    y = "Count",
    title = "1,000 randomized F statistics"
    )

  11. True / False: ANOVA, I. Determine if the following statements are true or false in ANOVA, and explain your reasoning for statements you identify as false.

    1. As the number of groups increases, the modified significance level for pairwise tests increases as well.

    2. As the total sample size increases, the degrees of freedom for the residuals increases as well.

    3. The constant variance condition can be somewhat relaxed when the sample sizes are relatively consistent across groups.

    4. The independence assumption can be relaxed when the total sample size is large.

  12. True / False: ANOVA, II. Determine if the following statements are true or false, and explain your reasoning for statements you identify as false.

    If the null hypothesis that the means of four groups are all the same is rejected using ANOVA at a 5% significance level, then

    1. we can then conclude that all the means are different from one another.

    2. the standardized variability between groups is higher than the standardized variability within groups.

    3. the pairwise analysis will identify at least one pair of means that are significantly different.

    4. the appropriate \(\alpha\) to be used in pairwise comparisons is 0.05 / 4 = 0.0125 since there are four groups.

  13. Matching observed data with randomized F statistics. Consider the following two datasets. The response variable is the score and the explanatory variable is whether the individual is in one of four groups.

    library(tidyverse)
library(infer)
library(patchwork)
set.seed(470)

data_A <- tibble(
  group = rep(c("Group 1", "Group 2", "Group 3", "Group 4"), each = 25),
  score = c(rnorm(25, 10, 5), rnorm(25, 5, 5), rnorm(25, 8, 5), rnorm(25, 2, 5))
  )

F_A <- data_A %>%
  specify(score ~ group) %>%
  calculate(stat = "F") %>% pull()

p_A <- data_A %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = group, y = score)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(y = "Score", title = "Dataset A")

rand_A <- data_A %>%
  specify(score ~ group) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "F") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = stat)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = IMSCOL["green", "full"]) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = F_A, color = IMSCOL["red", "full"]) +
  labs(x = "F statistic", y = "Count", title = "Right randomization")

data_B <- tibble(
  group = rep(c("Group 1", "Group 2", "Group 3", "Group 4"), each = 25),
  score = c(rnorm(25, 10, 20), rnorm(25, 5, 20), rnorm(25, 8, 20), rnorm(25, 2, 20))
  )

F_B <- data_B %>%
  specify(score ~ group) %>%
  calculate(stat = "F") %>% 
  pull()

p_B <- data_B %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = group, y = score)) +
  labs(y = "Score", title = "Dataset B")

rand_B <- data_B %>%
  specify(score ~ group) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(1000, type = "permute") %>%
  calculate(stat = "F") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = stat)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = IMSCOL["green", "full"]) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = F_B, color = IMSCOL["red", "full"], size = 1) +
  labs(x = "F statistic", y = "Count", title = "Left randomization")

p_A + p_B + rand_B + rand_A +
